{{About|the [[ethnolinguistic group]]|the ethnic group of [[Germany]]|Germans}}
{{Pp-protected|small=yes}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2012}}
[[File:Bronze figure of a German Bibliothèque Nationale.jpg|thumb|right|263px|[[Ancient Rome|Roman]] bronze statuette representing a [[Germanic paganism|praying]] Germanic man with his hair in a [[Suebian knot]]]]
{{Indo-European topics}}
The '''Germanic peoples''' (also called [[Theodiscus|Teutonic]], [[Suebi]]an, or [[Gaut|Gothic]] in older literature) are an [[Proto-Indo-Europeans|Indo-European]] [[ethnolinguistic group]] of [[Northern Europe|Northern European]] origin identified by their use of the [[Germanic languages]].{{sfn|Germanic peoples, ''Encyclopædia Britannica Online''}} Their history stretches from the [[2nd millennium BCE]] up to the present day.{{Efn|"GERMANICS location: Greater Europe time period: Second millennium B.C.E. to present ancestry: Germanic language: Germanic"{{sfn|Waldman|Mason|2006|p=296}}  }}

[[Proto-Germanic language|Proto-Germanic]] peoples are believed to have emerged during the [[Nordic Bronze Age]], which developed out of the [[Corded Ware Culture#Swedish-Norwegian Battle Axe culture|Battle Axe culture]] in southern [[Scandinavia]].{{sfn|History of Europe: The Germans and Huns, ''Encyclopædia Britannica Online''}} During the [[Iron Age]] various Germanic tribes began a southward expansion at the expense of [[Celts|Celtic peoples]], which led to [[Germanic Wars|centuries of sporadic violent conflict]] with [[ancient Rome]]. It is from Roman authors that the term "Germanic" originated. The decisive victory of [[Arminius]] at the [[Battle of the Teutoburg Forest]] in 9 CE is believed to have prevented the eventual [[Romanization (cultural)|Romanization]] of the Germanic peoples, and has therefore been considered a turning point in [[History of the world|world history]].{{Efn|"[[Theodor Mommsen|Mommsen]] referred to the Battle of the Teutoburg forest as a turning-point in world history."{{sfn|How the eagles were tamed, ''The Spectator''}} }} Germanic tribes settled the entire Roman frontier along the [[Rhine]] and the [[Danube]], and some established close relations with the Romans, often serving as [[Mardonius (philosopher)|royal tutors]] and mercenaries, sometimes even rising to the highest offices in the [[Military of ancient Rome|Roman military]]. Meanwhile, Germanic tribes expanded into [[Eastern Europe]], where the [[Goths]] subdued the local [[Iranian peoples|Iranian]] [[Eurasian nomads|nomads]] and came to dominate the [[Pontic Steppe]], simultaneously launching sea expeditions into the [[Balkans]] and [[Anatolia]] as far as [[Cyprus]].{{sfn|Beckwith|2009|pp=82–83}}{{sfn|Wolfram|1988|pp=86–89}}{{sfn|Ancient Rome: The Barbarian Invasions, ''Encyclopædia Britannica Online''}}

The westward expansion of the [[Huns]] into Europe in the late 4th century CE [[Migration period|pushed]] many Germanic tribes into the [[Western Roman Empire]]. Their vacated lands were filled by [[Slavs]]. Much of these territories were [[Ostsiedlung|reclaimed]] in following centuries.{{sfn|Germanic peoples, ''Encyclopædia Britannica Online''}} Other tribes [[Anglo-Saxon settlement of Britain|settled]] [[Great Britain]] and became known as the [[Anglo-Saxons]]. With the [[collapse of the Western Roman Empire]], a series of [[Barbarian kingdoms|Germanic kingdoms]] emerged, of which, [[Francia]] gained a dominant position. This kingdom formed the [[Holy Roman Empire]] under the leadership of [[Charlemagne]], who was officially recognized by [[Pope Leo III]] in 800 CE. Meanwhile, [[North Germanic peoples|North Germanic]] seafarers, commonly referred to as [[Vikings]], embarked on a massive expansion which led to the establishment of the [[Duchy of Normandy]], [[Kievan Rus']] and their settlement of the [[British Isles]] and the [[North Atlantic Ocean]] as far as [[Vinland|North America]]. With the North Germanic abandonment of [[Germanic paganism|their native religion]] in the 11th century, nearly all Germanic peoples had been converted to [[Christianity]].{{sfn|Germanic religion and mythology, ''Encyclopædia Britannica Online''}} With the [[Reformation]] initiated by [[Martin Luther]] in the 16th century, many Germanic nations embraced [[Protestantism]]. The resulting religious division resulted in the political fragmentation of much of [[Germanic-speaking Europe|Germanic Europe]].{{sfn|Waldman|Mason|2006|p=311-312}}

The Germanic migrations forged the main component of the population of modern [[Sweden]], [[Norway]], [[Denmark]], [[Iceland]], [[Germany]], [[Austria]], [[Switzerland]], [[Northern Italy]], the [[Netherlands]], [[Belgium]], [[Luxembourg]], northern and central [[France]], [[Lowland Scotland]] and [[England]].{{sfn|Minahan|2000|p=288}} The Germanic peoples were instrumental in shaping much of [[Western Europe]]'s history from the [[Early Middle Ages]] to now.{{sfn|Waldman|Mason|2006|pp=330-331}} 

