| races        = Gallifreyan/[[Time Lord]]s{{refn|group=note|The television series and people involved in its production repeatedly refer to the Time Lords as a species. In ''[[The War Games]]'' (1969), the [[Second Doctor]] says the Time Lords are "an immensely civilised race".<ref name="war games ten">{{cite serial |title=The War Games |title-link=The War Games |episode=Episode Ten |url= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Terrance |last=Dicks |author-link=Terrance Dicks |first2=Malcolm (writers) |last2=Hulke |author-link2=Malcolm Hulke |first3=David (director) |last3=Maloney |author-link3=David Maloney |credits= |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC1]] |date=21 June 1969 |season= |number= |minutes= |transcript= |transcripturl= }}</ref> Writer [[Malcolm Hulke]] and writer and script editor [[Terrance Dicks]] repeat this description in their 1972 book ''The Making of Doctor Who''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Hulke |first=Malcolm |author-link=Malcolm Hulke |last2=Dicks |first2=Terrance |author-link2=Terrance Dicks |date=1972 |title=The Making of Doctor Who |url= |location= |publisher=[[Piccolo Books]] |page=19 |isbn=0 330 23203 7 }}</ref> In ''[[The Time Warrior]]'' (1973–74), Commander [[List of Doctor Who villains#Linx|Linx]] quotes [[Sontaran]] military intelligence as describing the Time Lords as "A race of great technical achievement, but lacking the morale to withstand a determined assault."<ref name="time warrior 2">{{cite serial |title=The Time Warrior |title-link=The Time Warrior |episode=Part Two |url= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |credits= |first=Robert (writer) |last=Holmes |author-link=Robert Holmes (scriptwriter) |first2=Alan (director)| last2=Bromly |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC1]] |date=22 December 1973 |season= |number= |minutes= |transcript= |transcripturl=}}</ref> In ''[[Pyramids of Mars]]'' (1975), [[List of Doctor Who villains#Sutekh|Sutekh]] calls the Time Lords "a perfidious species".<ref>{{cite serial |title=Pyramids of Mars |title-link=Pyramids of Mars |episode=Part Four |url= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Stephen (writer) |last=Harris |first2=Paddy (director) |last2=Russell |author-link2=Paddy Russell |credits= |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC1]] |date=15 November 1975 |number= |minutes= |transcript= |transcripturl=}}</ref> In "[[School Reunion (Doctor Who)|School Reunion]]" (2006), the alien Krillitane Mr Finch calls the Time Lords "such a pompous race".<ref>{{Cite episode |title=School Reunion |episode-link=School Reunion (Doctor Who) |url= |accessdate= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Toby (writer) |last=Whithouse |author-link=Toby Whithouse |first2=James (director) |last2=Hawes |author-link2=James Hawes |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |date=29 April 2006 |season= |series-no=2 |number=3 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote= |language=}}</ref> In "[[Smith and Jones (Doctor Who)|Smith and Jones]]" (2007), the [[Tenth Doctor]] answers "what sort of species [he is]" with "I'm a Time Lord."<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Smith and Jones |episode-link=Smith and Jones (Doctor Who) |url= |accessdate= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Russell T (writer) |last=Davies |author-link=Russell T Davies |first2=Charles (director) |last2=Palmer |author-link2=Charles Palmer (director) |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |date=31 March 2007 |season= |series-no=3 |number=1 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote= |language=}}</ref> In "[[Human Nature (Doctor Who episode)|Human Nature]]" (2007), Tim Latimer hears a voice saying, "Last of the Time Lords, the last of that wise and ancient race."<ref name="human nature">{{Cite episode |title=Human Nature |episode-link=Human Nature (Doctor Who episode) |url= |accessdate= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Paul (writer) |last=Cornell |author-link=Paul Cornell |first2=Charles (director) |last2=Palmer |author-link2=Charles Palmer (director) |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]]|date=26 May 2007 |season= |series-no=3 |number=8 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote= |language=}}</ref> In "[[Utopia (Doctor Who)|Utopia]]" (2007), the Tenth Doctor answers "what species are you" with "Time Lord, last of."<ref name="utopia">{{Cite episode |title=Utopia |episode-link=Utopia (Doctor Who) |url= |accessdate= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Russell T (writer) |last=Davies |author-link=Russell T Davies |first2=Graeme (director) |last2=Harper |author-link2=Graeme Harper |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |date=16 June 2007 |season= |series-no=3 |number=11 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote= |language=}}</ref> In "[[The Sound of Drums]]" (2007), the Tenth Doctor calls the Time Lords "the oldest and most mighty race in the universe".<ref name="drums"/> In "[[Planet of the Dead]]" (2009), the Tenth Doctor says, "I come from a race of people called Time Lords."<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Planet of the Dead |episode-link=Planet of the Dead |url= |accessdate= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Russell T |last=Davies |author-link=Russell T Davies |first2=Gareth (writers)| last2=Roberts |author-link2=Gareth Roberts (writer) |first3=James (director) |last3=Strong |author-link3=James Strong (director) |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |date=11 April 2009 |season= |series-no= |number= |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote= |language=}}</ref> About sixteen minutes into "[[Let's Kill Hitler]]" (2011), a computer readout describes the "Pilot Species" of the Doctor's ship the [[TARDIS]] as "Time Lord".<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Let's Kill Hitler |episode-link=Let's Kill Hitler |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Richard (director) |last2=Senior |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |date=27 August 2011 |season= |series-no=6 |number=8 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> In "[[The Witch's Familiar]]" (2015), [[Davros]] describes a prophecy that spoke of a "hybrid creature [of] two great warrior races forced together to create a warrior greater than either," and believes that the creature being referred to was "half [[Dalek]], half Time Lord."<ref>{{Cite episode |title=The Witch's Familiar |episode-link=The Witch's Familiar |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Hettie (director) |last2=MacDonald |author-link2=Hettie MacDonald |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |date=26 September 2015 |season= |series-no=9 |number=2 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> In "[[Before the Flood (Doctor Who)|Before the Flood]]" (2015), the Fisher King describes the Time Lords as "the most warlike race in the galaxy".<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Before the Flood |episode-link=Before the Flood (Doctor Who) |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Toby (writer) |last=Whithouse |author-link=Toby Whithouse |first2=Daniel (director) |last2=O'Hara |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |date=10 October 2015 |season= |series-no=9 |number=4 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> In "[[Hell Bent (Doctor Who)|Hell Bent]]" (2015), the General describes the Hybrid as being "crossbred between two warrior races". He says it is supposed that these races are "the Daleks and the Time Lords".<ref name="hell bent">{{Cite episode |title=Hell Bent |episode-link=Hell Bent (Doctor Who) |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Rachel (director) |last2=Talalay |author-link2=Rachel Talalay |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |date=5 December 2015 |season= |series-no=9 |number=12 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> In "[[Knock Knock (Doctor Who)|Knock Knock]]" (2017), the [[Twelfth Doctor]] tells [[Bill Potts (Doctor Who)|Bill Potts]] the Time Lords are "my species".<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Knock Knock |episode-link=Knock Knock (Doctor Who) |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Mike (writer) |last=Bartlett |author-link=Mike Bartlett (playwright) |first2=Bill (director) |last2=Anderson |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |date=6 May 2017 |season= |series-no=10 |number=4 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> Writing in issue #356 of ''[[Doctor Who Magazine]]'', [[head writer]] and [[executive producer]] [[Russell T Davies]] describes the Time Lords as "the Doctor's race".<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Davies |first=Russell T |author-link=Russell T Davies |date=25 May 2005 |title=The Evasion of Time |url= |magazine=[[Doctor Who Magazine]] |location=Tunbridge Wells |publisher=[[Panini Comics|Panini Publishing Ltd]] |issue=356 |page=66 |access-date= }}</ref> In a special feature on the DVD set of ''[[The Invasion of Time]]'', script editor [[Anthony Read]] called the Time Lords "an interesting species to somebody coming in".<ref>{{cite AV media |people=[[Terrance Dicks|Dicks, Terrance]]; [[Alan Barnes (writer)|Barnes, Alan]]; [[Gary Russell|Russell, Gary]]; [[Anthony Read|Read, Anthony]] |date=2008 |title=The Rise & Fall of Gallifrey |trans-title= |medium= |language= |url= |access-date= |archive-url= |archive-date= |format= |time= |location= |publisher=[[BBC Worldwide]] |id=BBCDVD2586 |isbn= |oclc= |quote= |ref= }}</ref> In a special feature on the DVD and Blu-ray set of [[Doctor Who (series 8)|series 8]], actor [[Peter Capaldi]] said the Doctor belongs to "a race called the Time Lords".<ref>{{cite AV media |people= |first=Steven |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Peter |last2=Capaldi |author-link2=Peter Capaldi |first3=Jenna |last3=Coleman |author-link3=Jenna Coleman |date=2014 |year= |title=What is Doctor Who? |trans-title= |medium= |language= |url= |access-date= |archive-url= |archive-date= |format=DVD |time= |location= |publisher=[[BBC Worldwide]] |id=BBCDVD3935 |isbn= |oclc= |quote= |ref= }}</ref> Terrance Dicks recalled in a 2016 interview in ''The Essential Doctor Who'' magazine that during a discussion of ''The War Games'', producer [[Derrick Sherwin]] said the Doctor belongs to "this mysterious race called Time Lords".<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Dicks |first=Terrance |author-link=Terrance Dicks |last2=Wright |first2=Mark |date=March 2016 |title=Creation Theories |url= |magazine=The Essential Doctor Who |location=Tunbridge Wells |publisher=[[Panini Comics|Panini UK Ltd]] |issue=7: ''The Time Lords'' |page=24 |isbn=9781846532207 |access-date= }}</ref> The Time Lords are also referred to as a race by media outlets including the ''[[Radio Times]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2016-03-30/could-this-new-fan-theory-help-explain-why-the-doctor-has-never-been-a-woman |title=Could this new fan theory help explain why the Doctor has never been a woman? |last=Fullerton |first=Huw |date=30 March 2016 |website=[[Radio Times]] |publisher= |access-date=15 July 2017 |quote=Sure, we know the basics: Doctor Who’s race of Time Lords (including the Doctor, currently Peter Capaldi) are able to revitalise their body’s cells when facing death, resulting in them completely changing their appearance and parts of their personality and allowing them to live much, much longer. }}</ref> and ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/21/business/media/raising-bbc-americas-profile-focusing-on-new-york-campaign-spotlight.html |title=Campaign Promotes BBC America the Beautiful |last=Elliott |first=Stuart |date=21 February 2012 |website=[[The New York Times]] |publisher= |access-date=15 July 2017 |quote=The Doctor Who character belongs to a race known as time lords. |url-access=limited }}</ref> while a correction in a 2014 [[NPR]] article claims that "not all Gallifreyans are Time Lords".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/monkeysee/2014/08/22/342185850/tvs-new-doctor-who-has-an-old-connection-to-the-series |title=TV's New Doctor Who Has An Old Connection To The Series |last=Deggans |first=Eric |date=22 August 2014 |website=[[NPR]] |publisher= |access-date=15 July 2017 |quote=}}</ref> "The Stolen Tardis" (1979), a spin-off comic printed in issue #9 of ''Doctor Who Weekly'' (the original name of ''Doctor Who Magazine'') also claims that "not everyone on Gallifrey is a Time Lord",<ref>{{Cite comic | writer = [[Steve Moore (comics)|Moore, Steve]] | artist = [[Steve Dillon|Dillon, Steve]] | story = The Stolen Tardis: A Tale of the Time Lords: Part One | title = [[Doctor Who Weekly]] | volume = | issue = #9 | date = 12 December 1979 | publisher = [[Marvel UK]] | location = London | page = | panel = | id = }}</ref> while a feature in issue #21 instead states that the Doctor is "a member of a race called the Time Lords".<ref>{{cite magazine |date=5 March 1980 |title=The Time Lords of Gallifrey |url= |magazine=[[Doctor Who Weekly]] |location=London |publisher=[[Marvel UK]] |access-date= |issue=21 |page=10 }}</ref> }}
