'''Gallifrey''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|ɡ|æ|l|ᵻ|f|r|eɪ}} or {{IPAc-en|ˈ|ɡ|æ|l|ᵻ|f|r|iː}}) is a planet in the long-running British [[science fiction on television|science fiction television]] series ''[[Doctor Who]]''. It is the original home world of the [[Time Lord]]s, including [[Doctor (Doctor Who)|the Doctor]], [[The Master (Doctor Who)|the Master]] and [[The Rani (Doctor Who)|the Rani]]. It is located in a [[binary star system]]<ref name="gridlock">{{Cite episode |title=Gridlock |episodelink=Gridlock (Doctor Who) |url= |accessdate= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=Russell T (writer) |last=Davies |authorlink=Russell T Davies |first2=Richard (director) |last2=Clark |authorlink2=Richard Clark (director) |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=14 April 2007 |season= |seriesno=3 |number=3 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote= |language=}}</ref> within the constellation of Kasterborous,<ref name="pyramids">{{cite serial |title=[[Pyramids of Mars]] |episode= |url= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=Stephen (writer) |last=Harris |authorlink=Robert Holmes (scriptwriter) |first2=Paddy (director) |last2=Russell |authorlink2=Paddy Russell |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC1]] |city= |date=25 October – 15 November 1975 |season= |number= |minutes= |transcript= |transcripturl=}}</ref><ref>{{cite serial |title=[[Attack of the Cybermen]] |episode= |url= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=Paula (writer) |last=Moore |authorlink=Paula Moore |first2=Matthew (director) |last2=Robinson |authorlink2=Matthew Robinson (producer) |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC1]] |city= |date=5–12 January 1985 |season= |number= |minutes= |transcript= |transcripturl=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite episode |title=Voyage of the Damned |episodelink=Voyage of the Damned |url= |accessdate= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=Russell T (writer) |last=Davies |authorlink=Russell T Davies |first2=James (director) |last2=Strong |authorlink2=James Strong (director) |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=25 December 2007 |season= |seriesno= |number= |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote= |language=}}</ref> at "galactic coordinates ten-zero-eleven-zero-zero by zero-two from galactic zero centre".<ref name="pyramids"/><ref>{{cite serial |title=[[Full Circle (Doctor Who)|Full Circle]] |episode= |url= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=Andrew (writer) |last=Smith |first2=Peter (director) |last2=Grimwade |authorlink2=Peter Grimwade |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC1]] |city= |date=25 October – 15 November 1980 |season= |number= |minutes= |transcript= |transcripturl=}}</ref><ref name="heaven">{{Cite episode |title=Death in Heaven |episodelink=Death in Heaven |url= |accessdate= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |authorlink=Steven Moffat |first2=Rachel (director) |last2=Talalay |authorlink2=Rachel Talalay |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=8 November 2014 |season= |seriesno=8 |number=12 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote= |language=}}</ref>

During the first decade of the television series, the name of the Doctor's home planet was not revealed, although it was actually shown for the first time in ''[[The War Games]]'' (1969) during the [[Second Doctor]]'s trial.<ref name="war games ten"/> It was finally identified by name for the first time in ''[[The Time Warrior]]'' (1973–74).<ref name="time warrior 2"/> It is never definitively stated when the appearances of Gallifrey in the television series take place. As the planet is often reached by means of time travel, its relative present could conceivably exist almost anywhere in the [[Earth]]'s past or future.{{refn|group=note|''[[The Three Doctors (Doctor Who)|The Three Doctors]]'' (1972–73) seemed to{{original research inline|date=April 2015}} set Gallifrey's relative present contemporary with the events of the story set on Earth,<ref>{{cite serial |title=[[The Three Doctors (Doctor Who)|The Three Doctors]] |episode= |url= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=Bob |last=Baker |authorlink=Bob Baker (scriptwriter) |first2=Dave (writers) |last2=Martin |authorlink2=Dave Martin (screenwriter) |first3=Lennie (director) |last3=Mayne |authorlink3=Lennie Mayne |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC1]] |city= |date=30 January 1972 – 20 January 1973 |season= |number= |minutes= |transcript= |transcripturl=}}</ref> with its sequel ''[[Arc of Infinity]]'' (1983) setting it in the 1980s.<ref>{{cite serial |title=[[Arc of Infinity]] |episode= |url= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=Johnny (writer) |last=Byrne |authorlink=Johnny Byrne (writer) |first2=Ron (director) |last2=Jones |authorlink2=Ron Jones (television director) |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC1]] |city= |date=3–12 January 1983 |season= |number= |minutes= |transcript= |transcripturl=}}</ref> Alternatively, ''[[The Trial of a Time Lord]]'' (1986) seems to imply{{original research inline|date=April 2015}} that the planet's relative present is in the Earth's far future.<ref>{{cite serial |title=[[The Trial of a Time Lord]] |episode= |url= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=Robert |last=Holmes |authorlink=Robert Holmes (scriptwriter) |first2=Philip |last2=Martin |authorlink2=Philip Martin (screenwriter) |first3=Pip |last3=Baker |authorlink3=Pip and Jane Baker |first4=Jane (writers) |last4=Baker |authorlink4=Pip and Jane Baker |first5=Nicholas |last5=Mallett |authorlink5=Nicholas Mallett |first6=Ron |last6=Jones |authorlink6=Ron Jones (television director) |first7=Chris (directors) |last7=Clough |authorlink7=Chris Clough |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC1]] |city= |date=6 September – 6 December 1986 |season= |number= |minutes= |transcript= |transcripturl=}}</ref> This is also the position taken by ''[[The Doctor Who Role Playing Game]]'' released by [[FASA Corporation|FASA]], although the information in it is not usually considered [[canon (fiction)|canon]]. In the episode "[[Utopia (Doctor Who)|Utopia]]" (2007), the [[Tenth Doctor]] describes the year 100 trillion as a time period not even the Time Lords travelled to.<ref name="utopia"/> The present of Gallifrey from after it returns to the universe from another dimension is stated to be around the end of the universe, "several billion years in the future", in "[[Hell Bent (Doctor Who)|Hell Bent]]" (2015).<ref name="hell bent"/> Both the [[Virgin New Adventures]]{{vague|date=April 2015}}{{which|date=April 2015}}{{citation needed|date=April 2015}} and the [[BBC Books]] ''Doctor Who'' novels{{vague|date=April 2015}}{{which|date=April 2015}}{{citation needed|date=April 2015}} seem to{{original research inline|date=April 2015}} take the stance that Gallifrey's relative present is far in the Earth's relative past.}}

Gallifrey's position in the revived series (2005 onwards) was filled in slowly over the first three years of the series' run. In the [[Doctor Who (series 1)|series 1]] episode "[[The End of the World (Doctor Who)|The End of the World]]", the [[Ninth Doctor]] describes the planet as "rocks and dust", "dead [...] before its time" and having "burnt" like the Earth had done in the year 5 billion in a "[[Time War (Doctor Who)|war]]" the Doctor's people had lost.<ref name="end of the world">{{Cite episode |title=The End of the World |episodelink=The End of the World (Doctor Who) |url= |accessdate= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=Russell T (writer) |last=Davies |authorlink=Russell T Davies |first2=Euros (director) |last2=Lyn |authorlink2=Euros Lyn |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=2 April 2005 |season= |seriesno=1 |number=2 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote= |language=}}</ref> The planet was not referred to by name after the show's return in 2005 until the 2006 Christmas special, "[[The Runaway Bride (Doctor Who)|The Runaway Bride]]".<ref name="runaway bride">{{Cite episode |title=The Runaway Bride |episodelink=The Runaway Bride (Doctor Who) |url= |accessdate= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=Russell T (writer) |last=Davies |authorlink=Russell T Davies |first2=Euros (director) |last2=Lyn |authorlink2=Euros Lyn |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=25 December 2006 |season= |seriesno= |number= |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote= |language=}}</ref> It was depicted in a flashback in "[[The Sound of Drums]]" in [[Doctor Who (series 3)|series 3]]<ref name="drums"/> and played an important role in the plot of ''[[The End of Time (Doctor Who)|The End of Time]]'' (2009–10).<ref>{{cite serial |title=[[The End of Time (Doctor Who)|The End of Time]] |episode= |url= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=Russell T (writer) |last=Davies |authorlink=Russell T Davies |first2=Euros (director) |last2=Lyn |authorlink2=Euros Lyn |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=25 December 2009 – 1 January 2010 |season= |number= |minutes= |transcript= |transcripturl=}}</ref> It appeared briefly in the [[Doctor Who (series 7)|seventh series]] finale, "[[The Name of the Doctor]]", which shows the moment the [[First Doctor]] and [[Susan Foreman|Susan]] stole the [[TARDIS]].<ref name="name of the doctor">{{Cite episode |title=The Name of the Doctor |episodelink=The Name of the Doctor |url= |accessdate= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |authorlink=Steven Moffat |first2=Saul (director) |last2=Metzstein |authorlink2=Saul Metzstein |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=18 May 2013 |season= |seriesno=7 |number=13 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote= |language=}}</ref> Gallifrey is revealed at the conclusion of "[[The Day of the Doctor]]" (2013) to have survived the "(Great) Time War" and didn't burn as the Doctor originally believed, though it was frozen in time and shunted into another dimension,<ref name="the day of the doctor">{{Cite episode |title=The Day of the Doctor |episodelink=The Day of the Doctor |url= |accessdate= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |authorlink=Steven Moffat |first2=Nick (director) |last2=Hurran |authorlink2=Nick Hurran |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=23 November 2013 |season= |seriesno= |number= |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote= |language=}}</ref> before returning to the universe at some point before "[[Hell Bent (Doctor Who)|Hell Bent]]" (2015).<ref name="hell bent"/>

==Geography and appearances==
[[File:Gallifrey2.jpg|thumb|left|A Vardan spaceship approaches Gallifrey from space (from ''[[The Invasion of Time]]'')<ref name="invasion of time">{{cite serial |title=[[The Invasion of Time]] |episode= |url= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=David (writer) |last=Agnew |authorlink=David Agnew |first2=Gerald (director) |last2=Blake |authorlink2=Gerald Blake |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC1]] |city= |date=4 February – 11 March 1978 |season= |number= |minutes= |transcript= |transcripturl=}}</ref>]]
From space, Gallifrey is seen as a yellow-orange planet and was close enough to central space lanes for spacecraft to require clearance from Gallifreyan Space Traffic Control as they pass through its system.<ref name="invasion of time"/> The planet was protected from physical attack by an impenetrable barrier called the quantum force field, and from teleportation incursions by the transduction barrier—which could be reinforced to repel most levels of this type of technological attack.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Richards |first=Justin |authorlink=Justin Richards |last2= |first2= |date=October 2014 |title=Gallifrey |url= |journal=The Essential Doctor Who |publisher=[[Panini Comics|Panini UK Ltd]] |volume= |issue=3: ''Alien Worlds'' |page=31 |pages= |doi= |access-date= }}</ref>

The Time Lord's principal city, named The Capitol, comprises shining towers protected by a mighty glass dome. Outside the Capitol is a wilderness with plains of red grass, as mentioned by the Doctor in ''[[Gridlock (Doctor Who)|Gridlock]]'' and ''[[The End of Time (Doctor Who)|The End of Time]]''

The Doctor's granddaughter [[Susan Foreman|Susan]] first describes her home world (not named as "Gallifrey" at the time) as having bright, silver-leafed trees and a burnt orange sky at night in the serial ''[[The Sensorites]]'' (1964).<ref>{{cite serial |title=[[The Sensorites]] |episode= |url= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=Peter R. (writer) |last=Newman |authorlink=Peter R. Newman |first2=Mervyn |last2=Pinfield |authorlink2=Mervyn Pinfield |first3=Frank (directors) |last3=Cox |authorlink3=Frank Cox (director) |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC1]] |city= |date=20 June – 1 August 1964 |season= |number= |minutes= |transcript= |transcripturl=}}</ref> This casts an amber tint on anything outside the city, as seen in ''The Invasion of Time''.<ref name="invasion of time"/> However, Gallifrey's sky appears blue and Earth-like in ''[[The Five Doctors]]'' (1983) within the isolated Death Zone.<ref name="the five doctors">{{cite serial |title=[[The Five Doctors]] |episode= |url= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=Terrance (writer) |last=Dicks |authorlink=Terrance Dicks |first2=Peter (director) |last2=Moffatt |authorlink2=Peter Moffatt |network=[[PBS]] |station= |city= |date=23 November 1983 |season= |number= |minutes= |transcript= |transcripturl=}}</ref>

In ''[[The Time Monster]]'', the [[Third Doctor]] says that "When I was a little boy, we used to live in a house that was perched halfway up the top of a mountain", explaining, "I ran down that mountain and I found that the rocks weren't grey at all—but they were red, brown and purple and gold. And those pathetic little patches of sludgy snow were shining white. Shining white in the sunlight."<ref name="time monster">{{cite serial |title=[[The Time Monster]] |episode= |url= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=Robert (writer) |last=Sloman |authorlink=Robert Sloman |first2=Paul (director) |last2=Bernard |authorlink2=Paul Bernard (director) |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC1]] |city= |date=20 May – 24 June 1972 |season= |number= |minutes= |transcript= |transcripturl=}}</ref> In "[[Gridlock (Doctor Who)|Gridlock]]", the [[Tenth Doctor]] echoes Susan's description of the world now named as Gallifrey and goes further by mentioning the vast mountain ranges "with fields of deep red grass, capped with snow". He then elaborates how Gallifrey's second sun would "rise in the south and the mountains would shine", with the silver-leafed trees looking like "a forest on fire" in the mornings.<ref name="gridlock"/>

Outer Gallifrey's wastelands are where the "Outsiders" reside,<ref>{{cite journal |last=Richards |first=Justin |authorlink=Justin Richards |last2= |first2= |date=October 2014 |title=Gallifrey |url= |journal=The Essential Doctor Who |publisher=[[Panini Comics|Panini UK Ltd]] |volume= |issue=3: ''Alien Worlds'' |page=30 |pages= |doi= |access-date= }}</ref> [[The Doctor Who Role Playing Game]] released by [[FASA Corporation|FASA]] equates the Outsiders with the "Shobogans", who are briefly mentioned in the serial ''The Deadly Assassin''. The wastes of Gallifrey include the Death Zone, an area that was used as a [[gladiator]]ial arena by the first Time Lords, pitting various species kidnapped from their respective time zones against each other (although [[Dalek]]s and [[Cyberman|Cybermen]] were considered too dangerous to use). Inside the Death Zone stands the Tomb of [[Rassilon]], the founder of Time Lord society.<ref name="the five doctors"/>

Somewhere on Gallifrey there is also an institute called the Academy, which the Doctor and various other Time Lords have attended.<ref name="drums"/>

The 2013 minisode "[[The Last Day (Doctor Who)|The Last Day]]" mentions birds as something expected in Gallifrey's skies.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=The Last Day |episodelink=The Last Day (Doctor Who) |url= |accessdate= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |authorlink=Steven Moffat |first2=Jamie (director) |last2=Stone |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC Red Button]] |city= |date=21 November 2013 |season= |seriesno= |number= |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote= |language=}}</ref> Gallifrey appeared in the ''Doctor Who'' 50th anniversary special, "[[The Day of the Doctor]]" which aired on November 23, 2013.<ref name="the day of the doctor"/>

===Spin-off material===
Several of the [[Doctor Who spin-offs|spin-off]] novels have further information about Gallifrey. It is said to have at least two moons, one being the copper-coloured Pazithi Gallifreya (first named in ''[[Cat's Cradle: Time's Crucible]]'');<ref>{{cite book |last=Platt |first=Marc |authorlink=Marc Platt (writer) |title=[[Cat's Cradle: Time's Crucible]] |series=[[Virgin New Adventures]] |date=February 1992 |publisher=[[Virgin Books]] |location=London |isbn=0-426-20365-8 |pages=40 }}</ref> the novel ''[[Lungbarrow]]'' also places Karn (setting of ''[[The Brain of Morbius]]'', 1976) in Gallifrey's solar system, along with a frozen gas giant named Polarfrey and an "astrological figure" of "Kasterborous the Fibster".<ref>{{cite book |last=Platt |first=Marc |authorlink=Marc Platt (writer) |title=Lungbarrow |titlelink=Lungbarrow |url= |accessdate= |series=[[Virgin New Adventures]] |date=20 March 1997 |publisher=[[Virgin Books]] |location=London |isbn=0-426-20502-2 |pages=35}}</ref> ''Cat's Cradle: Time's Crucible'' also mentions edible rodent-like mammals called tafelshrews.<ref name="times crucible">{{cite book |last=Platt |first=Marc |authorlink=Marc Platt (writer) |date=February 1992 |title=Cat's Cradle: Time's Crucible |titlelink=Cat's Cradle: Time's Crucible |series=[[Virgin New Adventures]] |url= |location= |publisher=[[Virgin Books]] |page= |isbn=0-426-20365-8 |access-date= }}</ref>

==History==
:''For general Time Lord history, see [[History of the Time Lords]].''

===On screen===
[[File:Gallifrey.jpg|thumb|right| Gallifrey as seen in ''[[The End of Time (Doctor Who)|The End of Time]]'' by the side of the [[Earth]].<ref name="end of time two">{{cite serial |title=[[The End of Time (Doctor Who)|The End of Time]] |episode=Part Two |url= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=Russell T (writer) |last=Davies |authorlink=Russell T Davies |first2=Euros (director) |last2=Lyn |authorlink2=Euros Lyn |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=1 January 2010 |season= |number= |minutes= |transcript= |transcripturl=}}</ref>]]

Few details on the history of the planet itself emerge from the original series run from 1963–1989. In "[[The End of the World (Doctor Who)|The End of the World]]" (2005), the [[Ninth Doctor]] states that his home planet has been destroyed in a war and that he is the last of the Time Lords. The episode also indicates that the Time Lords are remembered in the far future.<ref name="end of the world"/>
<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Gallifrey Ruins.jpg|thumb|right|The Dome shattered and Dalek Saucers crashed.  (from ''[[The End of Time]]'')]] -->
Subsequently, in "[[Dalek (Doctor Who episode)|Dalek]]" (2005), it is revealed that the last great [[Time War (Doctor Who)|Time War]] was fought between the Time Lords and the [[Dalek]]s, ending in the obliteration of both sides and with only two apparent survivors; the Doctor and a lone Dalek that had somehow fallen through time and crashed on Earth. At the conclusion of that episode, that surviving Dalek self-destructs, leaving the Ninth Doctor believing that he was the sole survivor of the Time War.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Dalek |episodelink=Dalek (Doctor Who episode) |url= |accessdate= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=Robert (writer) |last=Shearman |authorlink=Robert Shearman |first2=Joe (director) |last2=Ahearne |authorlink2=Joe Ahearne |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=30 April 2005 |season= |seriesno=1 |number=6 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote= |language=}}</ref> However, the Daleks return in "[[Bad Wolf]]"/"[[The Parting of the Ways]]" (2005),<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Bad Wolf |episodelink=Bad Wolf |url= |accessdate= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=Russell T (writer) |last=Davies |authorlink=Russell T Davies |first2=Joe (director) |last2=Ahearne |authorlink2=Joe Ahearne |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=11 June 2005 |season= |seriesno=1 |number=12 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote= |language=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite episode |title=The Parting of the Ways |episodelink=The Parting of the Ways |url= |accessdate= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=Russell T (writer) |last=Davies |authorlink=Russell T Davies |first2=Joe (director) |last2=Ahearne |authorlink2=Joe Ahearne |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=18 June 2005 |season= |seriesno=1 |number=13 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote= |language=}}</ref> and subsequently in several other stories.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Army of Ghosts |episodelink=Army of Ghosts |url= |accessdate= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=Russell T (writer) |last=Davies |authorlink=Russell T Davies |first2=Graeme (director) |last2=Harper |authorlink2=Graeme Harper |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=1 July 2006 |season= |seriesno=2 |number=12 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote= |language=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite episode |title=Doomsday |episodelink=Doomsday (Doctor Who) |url= |accessdate= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=Russell T (writer) |last=Davies |authorlink=Russell T Davies |first2=Graeme (director) |last2=Harper |authorlink2=Graeme Harper |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=8 July 2006 |season= |seriesno=2 |number=13 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote= |language=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite episode |title=Daleks in Manhattan |episodelink=Daleks in Manhattan |url= |accessdate= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=Helen (writer) |last=Raynor |authorlink=Helen Raynor |first2=James (director) |last2=Strong |authorlink2=James Strong (director) |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=21 April 2007 |season= |seriesno=3 |number=4 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote= |language=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite episode |title=Evolution of the Daleks |episodelink=Evolution of the Daleks |url= |accessdate= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=Helen (writer) |last=Raynor |authorlink=Helen Raynor |first2=James (director) |last2=Strong |authorlink2=James Strong (director) |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=28 April 2007 |season= |seriesno=3 |number=5 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote= |language=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite episode |title=The Stolen Earth |episodelink=The Stolen Earth |url= |accessdate= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=Russell T (writer) |last=Davies |authorlink=Russell T Davies |first2=Graeme (director) |last2=Harper |authorlink2=Graeme Harper |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=28 June 2008 |season= |seriesno=4 |number=12 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote= |language=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite episode |title=Journey's End |episodelink=Journey's End (Doctor Who) |url= |accessdate= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=Russell T (writer) |last=Davies |authorlink=Russell T Davies |first2=Graeme (director) |last2=Harper |authorlink2=Graeme Harper |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=5 July 2008 |season= |seriesno=4 |number=13 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote= |language=}}</ref>

The [[Tenth Doctor]]'s reference to Gallifrey in "[[The Runaway Bride (Doctor Who)|The Runaway Bride]]" (2006) is the first time the name of his homeworld has been given onscreen since the new series began. The Doctor's revelation that he is from Gallifrey elicits terror from the [[List of Doctor Who villains#Empress of the Racnoss|Empress of the Racnoss]].<ref name="runaway bride"/> The Tenth Doctor in human form (as "John Smith") mentions Gallifrey in "[[Human Nature (Doctor Who)|Human Nature]]" (2007) and is asked if it was in Ireland;<ref name="human nature"/> this is the same question asked in the 1970s stories ''[[The Hand of Fear]]''<ref>{{cite serial |title=[[The Hand of Fear]] |episode= |url= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=Bob |last=Baker |authorlink=Bob Baker (scriptwriter) |first2=Dave (writers) |last2=Martin |authorlink2=Dave Martin (screenwriter) |first3=Lennie (director) |last3=Mayne |authorlink3=Lennie Mayne |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC1]] |city= |date=2–23 October 1976 |season= |number= |minutes= |transcript= |transcripturl=}}</ref> and ''[[The Invisible Enemy (Doctor Who)|The Invisible Enemy]]''.<ref>{{cite serial |title=[[The Invisible Enemy (Doctor Who)|The Invisible Enemy]] |episode= |url= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=Bob |last=Baker |authorlink=Bob Baker (scriptwriter) |first2=Dave (writers) |last2=Martin |authorlink2=Dave Martin (screenwriter) |first3=Derrick (director) |last3=Goodwin |authorlink3=Derrick Goodwin |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC1]] |city= |date=1–22 October 1977 |season= |number= |minutes= |transcript= |transcripturl=}}</ref>

The planet makes its first appearance in the revived series in "[[The Sound of Drums]]" (2007), where the Citadel, enclosed in a glass dome (as described by the Doctor in "[[Gridlock (Doctor Who)|Gridlock]]", 2007), is seen in flashback as the Doctor describes it.<ref name="drums"/><ref name="gridlock"/> Also seen is a ceremony initiating 8-year-old Gallifreyans — in particular the Master — into the Time Lord Academy.<ref name="drums"/>

''[[The End of Time (Doctor Who)|The End of Time]]'' (2009–10) once again featured Gallifrey. By the end of the war, Gallifrey is depicted in ruins. The dome of the main city, the Time Lord capital, the Citadel, is shattered and dozens of Dalek saucers have crashed on the plains below. The Master releases Gallifrey from its time lock. However, Gallifrey's reemergence is eventually stopped and reversed after it is made clear that the release of Gallifrey would lead to the Time Lords destroying time — in effect destroying the universe — in order to defeat the Daleks and ultimately to preserve the Time Lords at the expense of all creation. Lord President [[Rassilon]] also believes that this action would elevate them to a higher form of existence, becoming "creatures of consciousness". Upon realising the scope of Rassilon's plan for self-preservation, the Tenth Doctor recalls that [[War Doctor|the Doctor that fought in the Time War]] had attempted to stop them during the war. Eventually, the Master comes to the aid of the Tenth Doctor and prevents Rassilon and the rest of Gallifrey from coming through, breaking the link that held Gallifrey in relative time to 21st century Earth.<ref name="end of time two"/>

It is stated by the Tenth Doctor in ''The End of Time'' that Gallifrey is not how he and the Master knew it in their youth. Implying that the Time Lords had resorted to desperate and deplorable measures to fight the Daleks, the Doctor is willing to break his code of non-violence to stop the return of the Time Lords.<ref name="end of time two"/> This is reinforced within a short feature that discloses the hitherto unknown circumstances of the [[Eighth Doctor]]'s regeneration into the [[War Doctor]], entitled "[[The Night of the Doctor]]" (2013). A young pilot rejects assistance from the Eighth Doctor due to her fear of the Time Lords.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=The Night of the Doctor |episode-link=The Night of the Doctor |url= |accessdate= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=John (director) |last2=Hayes |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC Red Button]] |city= |date=14 November 2013 |season= |seriesno= |number= |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote= |language=}}</ref>

In the [[Doctor Who (series 7)|series seven]] finale, "[[The Name of the Doctor]]", two Gallifreyan mechanics were seen on Gallifrey watching the [[First Doctor]] and [[Susan Foreman|Susan]] steal a [[TARDIS]].<ref name="name of the doctor"/>

In the 50th anniversary special of the television series, "[[The Day of the Doctor]]" (2013), scenes are shown during the fall of Arcadia, Gallifrey's second city. Subsequently it is shown that Gallifrey wasn't actually destroyed. The final scenes depict three of the Doctor's incarnations—the Tenth Doctor, the [[Eleventh Doctor]] and the [[War Doctor]]; the interface of the weapon, the Moment, that was supposed to destroy the planet; and the Eleventh Doctor's companion [[Clara Oswald]] decide against destroying it. Instead, they freeze the planet in time within a parallel pocket universe. This occurs with the help of the other Doctors, including the [[Twelfth Doctor]], whose eyes alone are seen at this point. Instead of destroying Gallifrey, the Dalek fleet echelons open fire on and destroy each other.<ref name="the day of the doctor"/>

In "[[The Time of the Doctor]]" (2013), the Time Lords are depicted as trying to re-enter the universe through a crack in the Universe on the planet [[Trenzalore]]. They broadcast a message throughout space and time, the question "Doctor Who?", a question which only the Doctor could answer. When the Doctor answers, they will know that it is safe to leave. However, this message inadvertently attracts various races, including the [[Daleks]] and [[Cybermen]], to lay siege to Trenzalore; the Eleventh Doctor remaining to protect the inhabitants, but not wanting to release the Time Lords as this would mean the destruction of Trenzalore and the initiation of another Time War. Hundreds of years later, Clara convinces the Time Lords to help the Doctor, dying from old age in his final regeneration, and the crack closes, before reopening in the sky above Trenzalore. The Time Lords give the Doctor a new regeneration cycle, before the crack seals for good with the Time Lords still lost, but a newly regenerated [[Twelfth Doctor]] ready to find them.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=The Time of the Doctor |episodelink=The Time of the Doctor |url= |accessdate= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Jamie (director) |last2=Payne |author-link2=Jamie Payne |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=25 December 2013 |season= |series-no= |number= |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote= |language=}}</ref> In "[[Death in Heaven]]" (2014), [[Master (Doctor Who)|Missy]] tells the Twelfth Doctor that Gallifrey is located at its original coordinates. These claims prove to be false, leaving the Doctor distraught.<ref name="heaven"/>

The Twelfth Doctor returns to Gallifrey in "[[Heaven Sent (Doctor Who)|Heaven Sent]]" (2015), having taken the "long way around" through breaking a wall of [[List of fictional elements, materials, isotopes and atomic particles|azbantium]] after he is teleported inside his [[List of Doctor Who items#Confession Dial|confession dial]].<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Heaven Sent |episode-link=Heaven Sent (Doctor Who) |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Rachel (director) |last2=Talalay |author-link2=Rachel Talalay |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=28 November 2015 |season= |series-no=9 |number=11 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote= |language=}}</ref> In "[[Hell Bent (Doctor Who)|Hell Bent]]" (2015), Gallifrey is revealed to have come back from the universe it was frozen in, and is now situated "several billion years in the future, and [when] the universe is pretty much over" for its own protection. After Rassilon is deposed and exiled by the Twelfth Doctor, Gallifrey is seen in a much later period in the episode abandoned apart from the human immortal [[Ashildr]], who is protected in the Cloisters beneath the Citadel by a reality bubble.<ref name="hell bent"/>

===Novels===
Various spin-off novels have expanded on the history and nature of Gallifrey.

[[Marc Platt (writer)|Marc Platt]]'s novels ''[[Cat's Cradle: Time's Crucible]]'' and ''[[Lungbarrow]]'', provide a detailed backstory for the civilisation seen in the main series. In the Dark Times (occasionally mentioned in the televised serials such as ''[[The Five Doctors]]''), Gallifrey was at the centre of an empire covering dozens of worlds and continually being extended by heroes such as Prydonius (whom the Time Lord chapter is named after). Ancient Gallifreyans are all telepathic and were ruled by a female cult centred on a figure called the Pythia, who controlled the population through mysticism and prophecies. When the prophetic powers of the last of the Pythias failed her, Rassilion, Omega and a shadowy figure known as The Other seized power in the name of science and rationality. Seeing this, the Pythia committed suicide and cursed Gallifrey, killing all children in their wombs and making the world sterile. To combat this, Rassilion restructured society and used genetic looms to create new generations of Gallifreyans, who emerge from the looms as fully grown adults. Each of the Great Houses is allotted a total of forty-five cousins and given a regeneration cycle of thirteen lives. The Houses themselves are to some degree alive, in the same way TARDISes are, and the furniture can move about, occasionally growing into 'Drudges' who function as servants for the family. [[Doctor (Doctor Who)|The Doctor]] was loomed in the House of Lungbarrow in the mountains of South Gallifrey, but unique among the house's cousins, he has a belly button.<ref name="times crucible"/><ref>{{cite book |last=Platt |first=Marc |authorlink=Marc Platt (writer) |date=20 March 1997 |title=Lungbarrow |titlelink=Lungbarrow |series=[[Virgin New Adventures]] |url= |location= |publisher=[[Virgin Books]] |page= |isbn=0-426-20502-2 |access-date= }}</ref> This sterility backstory is contradicted by on screen depictions and descriptions of [[Master (Doctor Who)|the Master]] and the Doctor as children,<ref name="drums"/><ref name="time monster"/><ref>{{Cite episode |title=The Girl in the Fireplace |episode-link=The Girl in the Fireplace |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Euros (director) |last2=Lyn |author-link2=Euros Lyn |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=6 May 2006 |season= |series-no=2 |number=4 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote='''Reinette:''' You're in my memories. You walk among them. '''Tenth Doctor:''' If there's anything you don't want me to see, just imagine a door and close it. I won't look. Ooh, actually, there's a door, just there. You might wanna cl-- ooh. Actually, several. '''Reinette:''' To walk among the memories of another living soul. Do you ever get used to this? '''Tenth Doctor:''' I don't make a habit of it. '''Reinette:''' How can you resist? '''Tenth Doctor:''' What age are you? '''Reinette:''' So impertinent a question so early in the conversation. How promising. '''Tenth Doctor:''' No, not my question, theirs. You're twenty-three, and for some reason that means you're not old enough? Sorry, you might find old memories reawakening. Side effect. '''Reinette:''' Oh, such a lonely childhood. '''Tenth Doctor:''' It'll pass. Stay with me. '''Reinette:''' Oh, Doctor. So lonely. So very, very alone. '''Tenth Doctor:''' What do you mean, alone? You've never been alone in your life. When did you start calling me Doctor? '''Reinette:''' Such a lonely little boy. Lonely then and lonelier now. How can you bear it? '''Tenth Doctor:''' How did you do that? '''Reinette:''' A door once opened may be stepped through in either direction. |language=}}</ref><ref>{{cite serial |title=[[The End of Time (Doctor Who)|The End of Time]] |episode=Part Two |url= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=Russell T (writer) |last=Davies |authorlink=Russell T Davies |first2=Euros (director) |last2=Lyn |authorlink2=Euros Lyn |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=1 January 2010 |season= |number= |minutes= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote='''The Master:''' I don't know what I'd be without that noise. '''Tenth Doctor:''' Wonder what I'd be, without you. '''The Master:''' Yeah. '''Wilf:''' What does he mean? What noise?  '''The Master:''' It began on Gallifrey, as children. Not that you'd call it childhood, more a life of duty. Eight years old, I was taken for initiation to stare into the Untempered Schism. '''Wilf:''' What does that mean? '''Tenth Doctor:''' It's a gap in the fabric of reality. You can see into the Time Vortex itself, and it hurts.}}</ref><ref>{{cite serial |title=[[The End of Time (Doctor Who)|The End of Time]] |episode=Part Two |url= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=Russell T (writer) |last=Davies |authorlink=Russell T Davies |first2=Euros (director) |last2=Lyn |authorlink2=Euros Lyn |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=1 January 2010 |season= |number= |minutes= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote='''Chancellor:''' The signal has been sent. The simple task of four beats transmitted back through time and implanted in the Master's mind as a child. '''Rassilon:''' Then we have a link to where the Master is right now.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite episode |title=Listen |episode-link=Listen (Doctor Who) |url= |accessdate= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Douglas (director) |last2=Mackinnon |author-link2=Douglas Mackinnon |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=13 September 2014 |season= |series-no=8 |number=4 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote= |language=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite episode |title=Death in Heaven |episode-link=Death in Heaven |url= |accessdate= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Rachel (director) |last2=Talalay |author-link2=Rachel Talalay |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=8 November 2014 |season= |series-no=8 |number=12 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote='''Osgood:''' Who is she? '''Twelfth Doctor:''' You'd never believe me if I told you. '''Osgood:''' Because I thought she might be the Master, regenerated into female form. Your childhood friend, responsible for a number of previous incursions. '''Twelfth Doctor:''' That was fairly quick. |language=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite episode |title=Death in Heaven |episode-link=Death in Heaven |url= |accessdate= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Rachel (director) |last2=Talalay |author-link2=Rachel Talalay |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=8 November 2014 |season= |series-no=8 |number=12 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote='''Twelfth Doctor:''' PE. PE. PE. '''Danny:''' Sir. '''Twelfth Doctor:''' I had a friend, once. We ran together when I was little. And I thought we were the same. When we grew up, we weren't. And now, she's trying to tear the world apart, and I can't run fast enough to hold it together. The difference is this. Pain is a gift. Without the capacity for pain, we can't feel the hurt we inflict. |language=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite episode |title=Heaven Sent |episode-link=Heaven Sent (Doctor Who) |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Rachel (director) |last2=Talalay |author-link2=Rachel Talalay |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=28 November 2015 |season= |series-no=9 |number=11 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote='''Twelfth Doctor:''' When I was a very little boy, there was an old lady who died. They covered her in veils, but it was a hot, sunny day, and the flies came. Gave me nightmares for years. So who's been stealing my nightmares? |language=}}</ref> the [[Eleventh Doctor]] stating he slept in the cot he brings out of his TARDIS<ref>{{Cite episode |title=A Good Man Goes to War |episodelink=A Good Man Goes to War |url= |accessdate= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |authorlink=Steven Moffat |first2=Peter (director) |last2=Hoar |authorlink2=Peter Hoar |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=4 June 2011 |season= |seriesno=6 |number=7 |minutes=31 |time= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote='''Amy:''' But you always hold out on us. Please, not this time. Doctor, it's our baby. Tell us something, one little thing. '''Eleventh Doctor:''' It's mine. '''Rory:''' What is? '''Eleventh Doctor:''' Cot. It's my cot. I slept in there. '''Amy:''' Oh my god, it's the Doctor's first stars. |language=}}</ref> and references made to the Doctor and the Master having parents,<ref>{{cite serial |title=[[Doctor Who (film)|Doctor Who]] |episode= |url= |series= |first=Matthew (writer) |last=Jacobs |authorlink=Matthew Jacobs |first2=Geoffrey (director) |last2=Sax |authorlink2=Geoffrey Sax |network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] |station= |city= |date=14 May 1996 |season= |number= |minutes= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote='''Grace:''' Maybe you're the result of some weird genetic experiment. '''Eighth Doctor:''' I don't think so. '''Grace:''' But you have no recollection of family? '''Eighth Doctor:''' No... No, no, no, no. Wait, wait, wait, wait. I remember, I'm with my father, we're lying back in the grass, it's a warm Gallifreyan night... '''Grace:''' Gallifreyan? '''Eighth Doctor:''' Gallifrey. Yes, this must be where I live. }}</ref><ref>{{Cite episode |title=The Fires of Pompeii |episodelink=The Fires of Pompeii |url= |accessdate= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=James (writer) |last=Moran |authorlink=James Moran (writer) |first2=Colin (director) |last2=Teague |authorlink2=Colin Teague |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=12 April 2008 |season= |seriesno=4 |number=2 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote='''Quintus:''' Don't tell my dad. '''Tenth Doctor:''' Only if you don't tell mine. |language=}}</ref><ref>{{cite serial |title=[[The End of Time (Doctor Who)|The End of Time]] |episode=Part One |url= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=Russell T (writer) |last=Davies |authorlink=Russell T Davies |first2=Euros (director) |last2=Lyn |authorlink2=Euros Lyn |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=25 December 2009 |season= |number= |minutes= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote='''The Master:''' I had estates. Do you remember my father's land back home? Pastures of red grass stretching far across the slopes of Mount Perdition. We used to run across those fields all day, calling up at the sky. Look at us now. }}</ref> the Doctor himself being a father<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Fear Her |episodelink=Fear Her |url= |accessdate= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=Matthew (writer) |last=Graham |authorlink=Matthew Graham |first2=Euros (director) |last2=Lyn |authorlink2=Euros Lyn |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=24 June 2006 |season= |seriesno=2 |number=11 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote='''Rose:''' Oi, I've got cousins. Kids can't have it all their own way. That's part of being a family. '''Tenth Doctor:''' And what about trying to understand them? '''Rose:''' Easy for you to say. You don't have kids. '''Tenth Doctor:''' I was a dad, once. '''Rose:''' What did you say? |language=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite episode |title=The Doctor's Daughter |episodelink=The Doctor's Daughter |url= |accessdate= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=Stephen (writer) |last=Greenhorn |authorlink=Stephen Greenhorn |first2=Alice (director) |last2=Troughton |authorlink2=Alice Troughton |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=10 May 2008 |season= |seriesno=4 |number=6 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote='''Tenth Doctor:''' Donna, I've been a father before. '''Donna:''' What? '''Tenth Doctor:''' Lost all that a long time ago, along with everything else. '''Donna:''' I'm sorry. I didn't know. Why didn't you tell me? You talk all the time, but you don't say anything. |language=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite episode |title=Listen |episode-link=Listen (Doctor Who) |url= |accessdate= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Douglas (director) |last2=Mackinnon |author-link2=Douglas Mackinnon |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=13 September 2014 |season= |series-no=8 |number=4 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcripturl= |quote='''Rupert:''' Would you read me a story, or help me get to sleep? '''Clara:''' Sure. '''Twelfth Doctor:''' Once upon a time, the end. Dad skills. |language=}}</ref> and the Master having a daughter.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=The Witch's Familiar |episode-link=The Witch's Familiar |url= |access-date= |series=Doctor Who |series-link=Doctor Who |first=Steven (writer) |last=Moffat |author-link=Steven Moffat |first2=Hettie (director) |last2=MacDonald |author-link2=Hettie MacDonald |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |city= |date=26 September 2015 |season= |series-no=9 |number=2 |minutes= |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |quote='''Missy:''' Dark star alloy. Goes through armour plating like a knife through people. '''Clara:''' Missy. Missy. Missy, uncuff me, now. '''Missy:''' It's pretty though, isn't it? Got it on the olden days of Gallifrey, and the Doctor gave it to me when my daughter— Keep it talking. We need to draw it out of the lift. |language=}}</ref>

The [[Virgin New Adventures]]{{vague|date=April 2015}}{{which|date=April 2015}}{{citation needed|date=April 2015}} establish a religion on Gallifrey centred around the three main gods, Time, Death and Pain. The Time Lords use these figures to understand the concepts they represent and in some cases make deals with them and become their chosen champions. The [[Seventh Doctor]] is Time's Champion (as well as someone who makes frequent deals with or wages against Death to save his friends){{citation needed|date=April 2015}} and the audio play ''[[Master (audio drama)|Master]]'' states that the Master is Death's champion.<ref>{{cite serial |title=[[Master (audio drama)|Master]] |episode= |url= |series=Doctor Who: Main Range |serieslink=List of Doctor Who audio plays by Big Finish#Monthly releases |first=Joseph (writer) |last=Lidster |authorlink=Joseph Lidster |first2=Gary (director) |last2=Russell |authorlink2=Gary Russell |network= |station= |publisher=[[Big Finish Productions]] |city= |date=October 2003 |season= |number= |minutes= |transcript= |transcripturl=}}</ref> It's also briefly implied in ''[[Vampire Science]]'', that the [[Eighth Doctor]] is Life's champion, implying the existence of another unseen figure.<ref>{{cite book |last=Blum |first=Jonathan |authorlink=Jonathan Blum (writer, born 1972) |first2=Orman |last2=Kate |authorlink2=Kate Orman |date=July 1997 |title=Vampire Science |titlelink=Vampire Science |series=[[Eighth Doctor Adventures]] |url= |location= |publisher=[[BBC Books]] |page= |isbn=0-563-40566-X |access-date= }}</ref> ''[[Happy Endings (Doctor Who)|Happy Endings]]'' and other books imply that these gods are [[Eternal (Doctor Who)|Eternals]] as seen in the serial ''[[Enlightenment (Doctor Who)|Enlightenment]]''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Cornell |first=Paul |authorlink=Paul Cornell |date=May 1996 |title=Happy Endings |titlelink=Happy Endings (Doctor Who) |series=[[Virgin New Adventures]] |url= |location= |publisher=[[Virgin Books]] |page= |isbn=0-426-20470-0 |access-date= }}</ref><ref>{{cite serial |title=[[Enlightenment (Doctor Who)|Enlightenment]] |episode= |url= |series=Doctor Who |serieslink=Doctor Who |first=Barbara (writer) |last=Clegg |authorlink=Barbara Clegg |first2=Fiona (director) |last2=Cumming |authorlink2=Fiona Cumming |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC1]] |city= |date=1–9 March 1983 |season= |number= |minutes= |transcript= |transcripturl=}}</ref>

In the [[Eighth Doctor Adventures]] novel ''[[The Ancestor Cell]]'' by [[Peter Anghelides]] and [[Stephen Cole (writer)|Stephen Cole]], Gallifrey is destroyed as a result of the [[Eighth Doctor]]'s desire to prevent the voodoo cult [[Faction Paradox]] from starting a war between the Time Lords and an unnamed Enemy.<ref name="ancestor cell">{{cite book |last=Anghelides |first=Peter |authorlink=Peter Anghelides |last2=Cole |first2=Stephen |authorlink2=Stephen Cole (writer) |date=July 2000 |title=The Ancestor Cell |titlelink=The Ancestor Cell |series=[[Eighth Doctor Adventures]] |url= |location= |publisher=[[BBC Books]] |page= |isbn=0-563-53809-0 |access-date= }}</ref> Hints about this future war are dropped in several books earlier in the series{{vague|date=April 2015}}{{which|date=April 2015}}{{citation needed|date=April 2015}} beginning with [[Lawrence Miles]]' ''[[Alien Bodies]]''. In order to have boltholes or decoys in case of attack, the Time Lords have created nine separate planet Gallifreys (it even hinted that the original Gallifrey may at some point be reduced to ruins) and special looms to constantly produce new soldiers. By this time TARDISes have evolved to point where they appear human and reproduce sexually (the Doctor's companion [[Compassion (Doctor Who)|Compassion]] is the first such TARDIS). It is also hinted that the [[Celestial Intervention Agency]] will evolve into the beings of pure thought known as the Celestis, who observe the war from outside this dimension (the Last Parliament in which they sit resembles the Panopticon on Gallifrey and the closest anyone gets to describing them is similar to the Time Lords' robes). Faction Paradox itself is a counter to Time Lord society, dedicated to creating time-travel paradoxes, in contrast to the Time Lords' web of time. It was founded by a mysterious figure Grandfather Paradox, who it is believed was once a Time Lord from the House of Lungbarrow.{{citation needed|date=April 2015}} ''The Ancestor Cell'' suggests that he is a future version of the Doctor,<ref name="ancestor cell"/> but this is retconned in ''[[The Gallifrey Chronicles (Doctor Who novel)|The Gallifrey Chronicles]]'', to him being everyone's potential future self.<ref name="gallifrey chronicles">{{cite book |last=Parkin |first=Lance |authorlink=Lance Parkin |date=June 2005 |title=The Gallifrey Chronicles |titlelink=The Gallifrey Chronicles (Doctor Who novel) |series=[[Eighth Doctor Adventures]] |url= |location= |publisher=[[BBC Books]] |page= |isbn=0-563-48624-4 |access-date= }}</ref> When the Doctor destroys Gallifrey the war no longer happens and his actions also apparently (and retroactively) wipe the Time Lords from history.{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}

In the last regular Eighth Doctor novel, ''The Gallifrey Chronicles'' by [[Lance Parkin]], it is revealed that while Gallifrey was destroyed, the Time Lords were not erased from history. However, the cataclysm sets up an [[event horizon]] in time that prevents anyone from entering Gallifrey's relative past or travelling from it to the present or future. The Time Lords also survive within the Matrix, which has been downloaded into the Eighth Doctor's mind, but their reconstruction requires a sufficiently advanced computer. At the novel's end, the question of whether or not the Time Lords will be restored remains unanswered.<ref name="gallifrey chronicles"/>

Television series executive producer [[Russell T Davies]] wrote in ''[[Doctor Who Magazine]]'' #356 that there is no connection between the War of the books and the Time War of the television series.<ref name="RTDDWM">{{cite journal | first=Russell T | last=Davies | authorlink=Russell T Davies | title=The Evasion of Time| journal=[[Doctor Who Magazine]] | issue=356|publisher=[[Panini Comics]] | pages=66–67 | date=25 May 2005 }}</ref> In the same ''Doctor Who Magazine'' column, Davies compared Gallifrey being destroyed twice with Earth's two World Wars. He also said that he was "usually happy for old and new fans to invent the Complete History of the Doctor in their heads, completely free of the production team's hot and heavy hands".<ref name="RTDDWM" />

